columns.text:
The constant dividend growth model, as the name suggests, is a model in which the dividend of a company is predicted to grow at a constant rate forever. The model is represented as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}&=\dfrac{\text{D}\times(1+\text{g})^\text{t}}{\text{r}-\text{g}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}&=\text{Stock price}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Dividend}\\
\text{g}&=\text{Growth rate}\\
\text{t}&=\text{Time}\\
\text{r}&=\text{Required rate of return}
\end{aligned}$$

From the model above, we can represent the stock price at a certain time as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}\times(1+\text{g})^{t}&=\dfrac{\text{P}}{2(\text{r}-\text{g})}
\end{aligned}$$


Since there is an assumption that at time $t$, half of the company's stock price is equal to $t$ years worth of the company's dividends.

Simplifying this further by dividing both sides by $\text{P}$ to remove it, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
(1+\text{g})^t&=\dfrac{1}{2(\text{r}-\text{g})}
\end{aligned}$$

We can then recall the rules of logarithms known as the logarithm of powers which is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{ln}(\text{x})^y&=\text{y} \text{ln(x)}
\end{aligned}$$

This will allow us to rewrite the left side of the equation as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{t}\ \ln (1+\text{g})&=\ln\dfrac{1}{2(\text{r}-\text{g})}
\end{aligned}$$

Isolating the variable of time, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{t}&=\dfrac{\ln\frac{1}{2(\text{r}-\text{g})}}{\ln(1+\text{g})}
\end{aligned}$$

This equation now represents how many years worth of dividends constitute half of the company's current stock price using the constant dividend growth rate model.
